00:56:55,400 --> 00:57:13,001
Skipping down in the sort of about 15 lines from the bottom: no dying Chaldee or Greek had higher and holier thoughts than those whose mysterious shades you saw creeping over the face of poor Quequeg as he quietly lay in his swaying handle.

618
00:57:13,001 --> 00:57:17,801
So there's something absolutely holy about his life.

619
00:57:17,800 --> 00:57:18,520
Healed.

620
00:57:18,840 --> 00:57:34,121
If anybody's healed of the sickness that seems to be almost universal, according to Melville, I don't know whether he thinks everybody's cracked about the head or everybody but virtuous pagans.

621
00:57:34,121 --> 00:57:40,281
I think maybe he thinks everybody is, but the pagans managed to find a life in which you can heal.

622
00:57:40,280 --> 00:57:42,441
He's holy, he's healed.

623
00:57:42,441 --> 00:57:59,240
And that's because he's saved from non-total from totalizing religion so that he can see the sacred power of the various things in his religion.

624
00:57:59,240 --> 00:58:03,641
And there are several features of Quequeg now that are very important.

625
00:58:05,001 --> 00:58:12,400
This is Melville, one of Melville's attempts to show sort of what the ideal way to live in this meaningless universe is.

626
00:58:12,720 --> 00:58:18,001
So, one, Kwequeg doesn't try to put his religion and his gods off on others.

627
00:58:18,001 --> 00:58:23,360
That happens only if it all happens at all, because he gets corrupted by Christianity.

628
00:58:23,360 --> 00:58:28,800
And even then, I don't think you see him ever trying to even get Ishmael to worship Yo-Yo.

629
00:58:28,800 --> 00:58:31,041
That's Ishmael's idea.

630
00:58:31,041 --> 00:58:32,961
And now comes a new element.

631
00:58:32,961 --> 00:58:45,041
Kwequeg understands in a funny way, not an intellectual understanding, something about the sacredness of his own background practices.

632
00:58:45,280 --> 00:58:54,961
There is that he's got an understanding of being, but a plural understanding of being, not a mono-one.

633
00:58:56,641 --> 00:59:03,921
He was just socialized and raised up in a culture that has that, and he understands that that's sacred.

634
00:59:03,920 --> 00:59:05,440
So, how do we see that?

635
00:59:05,441 --> 00:59:06,880
Well, very peculiar.

636
00:59:06,880 --> 00:59:13,281
When he's dying and he's in his coffin, he copies out the markings on his body.

637
00:59:13,280 --> 00:59:18,321
This is Melville at his best, I think, because at least I can understand him.

638
00:59:19,200 --> 00:59:22,321
And yet he's saying weird, far-out things.

639
00:59:22,320 --> 00:59:39,521
At the 464 with the first full paragraph, with a wild, whimsic whimsiness, he now used his coffin, this is Kwequeg, for a sea chest and emptied into it his canvas bag of clothes and set them in order.

640
00:59:39,521 --> 00:59:41,040
And now comes the part for us.

641
00:59:41,041 --> 00:59:48,481
More spare hours he spent in carving the lid of all, carving the lid with all manner of grotesque figures and drawings.

642
00:59:48,481 --> 00:59:55,161
And it seems that thereby he was striving in his rude way to copy parts of the twisted tattooing on his body.

643
00:59:55,161 --> 00:59:57,481
Now, that's very interesting.

644
00:59:57,481 --> 01:00:00,840
By the way, the coffin turns out to be very important and what's carved on it.

645
01:00:00,920 --> 01:00:04,281
I can't tell you more about why for a while.

646
01:00:04,280 --> 01:00:20,521
And this tattooing had been the work of a departed prophet and seer of his island, who, by those hieroglyphic marks, had written out on his body a complete theory of the heavens and the earth and a mystical treatise on the art of attaining truth.

647
01:00:20,840 --> 01:00:30,121
So in his body, he contains, so to speak, an understanding of the universe.

648
01:00:30,121 --> 01:00:34,121
Now, I think it's a big mistake to say a complete theory of the heavens.

649
01:00:34,121 --> 01:00:37,081
That's too scientific and too modern.

650
01:00:37,240 --> 01:00:39,081
Melville just slips up there.

651
01:00:39,081 --> 01:00:40,040
He doesn't believe.

652
01:00:40,041 --> 01:00:44,200
He says explicitly that he doesn't believe there's any complete theory of anything.

653
01:00:44,200 --> 01:00:45,161
And that's right.

654
01:00:45,161 --> 01:00:47,880
That's his view about science and everything else.

655
01:00:47,880 --> 01:00:49,561
I don't know how he could do that.

656
01:00:50,360 --> 01:00:57,481
But it is something like an understanding of the universe and our place in it.

657
01:00:57,481 --> 01:01:04,041
That's the theory, that's what he has of the heaven and the earth and the art of attaining truth.

658
01:01:04,041 --> 01:01:17,321
He's got all that carved on his body, but so that Kleeque in his own proper person was a riddle to behold, a wondrous work in one volume, but whose mysteries not even himself could read.

659
01:01:17,641 --> 01:01:19,641
Now, what does that mean?

660
01:01:19,641 --> 01:01:20,681
That's very weird.

661
01:01:20,681 --> 01:01:23,001
What is Melville talking about?

662
01:01:23,320 --> 01:01:39,601
And the answer is: we are all that, each of us have in our body an understanding of being that we get from our culture, which is in a certain way sacred because it thanks to it, anything shows up as anything.

663
01:01:39,601 --> 01:01:43,361
And anything makes whatever makes sense to do makes sense to do.

664
01:01:44,001 --> 01:01:48,881
I think I gave you examples last time, but I'll talk about it again a little.

665
01:01:48,880 --> 01:01:58,961
We all stand a certain distance from each other in this culture, and that's related to how much whom we put our arms around, and that's related to what intimacy amounts to.

666
01:01:59,521 --> 01:02:01,361
And I made another one here.

667
01:02:01,360 --> 01:02:09,521
It's in the culture where women are submissive, then there's a whole understanding of their role in the world.

668
01:02:09,521 --> 01:02:26,401
Then they don't have to think about it, they don't have to notice it, they won't think about it, they don't notice it, but they stand stooped over, they don't look people in the eye, they speak quietly, they follow behind their husband, they don't interrupt the men when they're talking seriously, and so forth.

669
01:02:26,400 --> 01:02:28,960
That's the truth about women in the culture.

670
01:02:28,961 --> 01:02:29,760
That's what it means.

671
01:02:30,001 --> 01:02:41,041
And in those women, that truth is carved onto their bodies, and they don't understand it, they don't see it, they can't read it.

672
01:02:41,601 --> 01:02:45,761
That's exactly what Melville has gotten to here.

673
01:02:46,001 --> 01:02:47,601
He may be the first one to say this.

674
01:02:47,601 --> 01:02:50,240
Philosophers have never, never noticed that.

675
01:02:50,561 --> 01:02:53,520
Yeats noticed it, poets noticed it.

676
01:02:53,760 --> 01:03:02,961
I've got a thing in my office, a poster, where Yeats, in the last letter he wrote, says, We can embody the truth, but we cannot know it.

677
01:03:02,961 --> 01:03:05,760
That's exactly what's happening with Quiqued.

678
01:03:05,760 --> 01:03:13,840
He embodies the truth of his culture, and he understands, he lives that truth, but he can't think that truth.

679
01:03:13,840 --> 01:03:18,401
He can't understand what's carved into his body.

680
01:03:18,400 --> 01:03:20,720
And Ahab at the end is wonderful.

681
01:03:20,720 --> 01:03:26,040
I said I would give you another quote about how Ahab can't stand uncertainty.

682
01:03:28,280 --> 01:03:35,321
And this thought, namely that he can't understand it, and it will remain unsolved to the last.

683
01:03:35,641 --> 01:03:48,601
This thought it must have been which suggested to Ahab that wild exclamation of his when one morning turning away from surveying poor Queque, oh devilish tantalization of the gods.

684
01:03:48,601 --> 01:03:50,841
And see, that adds a whole element.

685
01:03:50,840 --> 01:04:02,601
I mean, it's all very well to have the meaning of being in your culture carved into your body, and it's sacred, and you go to put it in your coffin and die happily with it.

686
01:04:03,240 --> 01:04:05,080
But Ahab can't stand that.

687
01:04:05,081 --> 01:04:17,001
He wants, it tantalizes him to read the hieroglyphics, to have the theory, to state the truth that's carved into Quequeg's body, and presumably the one that's in his body too.

688
01:04:17,720 --> 01:04:25,401
Ahab sees it as this unacceptable uncertainty, something like that.

689
01:04:25,400 --> 01:04:31,161
For him, it's got to be explicit, and if he can't read it, then he can't stand it.

690
01:04:31,400 --> 01:04:34,041
And that's just typical Ahab.

691
01:04:34,360 --> 01:04:42,681
So, and that's, and it's saving power of these sacred practices that are in the body of Quequeg.

692
01:04:42,760 --> 01:04:45,240
It doesn't require that he understand it.

693
01:04:45,240 --> 01:04:47,800
In fact, I think it would be lost if you understand it.

694
01:04:47,800 --> 01:04:53,160
Picture the women in that culture who have all this built into them that they are submissive.

695
01:04:53,160 --> 01:05:06,561
It would be the first stage of feminine rebellion and consciousness raising and breaking out of it if they saw that they had been socialized into it.

696
01:05:07,120 --> 01:05:09,681
And they would lose that understanding of being.

697
01:05:06,120 --> 01:05:11,280
And in a way, of course, that would be a good thing.

698
01:05:11,441 --> 01:05:14,240
Not all understandings of being are as good as any other.

699
01:05:14,720 --> 01:05:20,160
From our point of view, they could become women like women are in this culture.

700
01:05:20,160 --> 01:05:24,880
From maybe from their point of view, women in this culture have lost their essential femininity.

701
01:05:24,880 --> 01:05:26,800
We shouldn't get lost into those issues.

702
01:05:26,800 --> 01:05:36,880
The important thing is that it doesn't have to be made explicit, but Ahab can't stand it unless it's made explicit.

703
01:05:38,080 --> 01:05:39,840
Ahab can't stand.

704
01:05:40,401 --> 01:05:43,040
Remember, it's unrepresentable.

705
01:05:43,201 --> 01:05:47,280
The tattoos should remind you of the hieroglyphics on Moby Dick.

706
01:05:47,281 --> 01:05:54,320
Hieroglyphics are signs that mean something, but we can't tell what in Moby Dick, in the book.

707
01:05:54,321 --> 01:06:02,800
And what Ahab can't stand is the unrepresentable and the ungraspable and the uncertain.

708
01:06:02,800 --> 01:06:07,440
So he can't stand the Kwequeg squiggles.

709
01:06:08,401 --> 01:06:13,361
Now, I'll begin the next one because I don't want to.

710
01:06:13,521 --> 01:06:15,920
Well, no, now I, I mean, you want to say anything about that?

711
01:06:15,920 --> 01:06:23,200
That's a fascinating little riff there that it seems completely out of place.

712
01:06:23,201 --> 01:06:37,120
But when the time comes, remember that there's a, like, on Kweequeg's coffin is carved the saving meaning in the practices of the culture.

713
01:06:37,441 --> 01:06:41,280
And that will turn out to be interesting and important.

714
01:06:41,281 --> 01:06:44,800
Well, now let me, I'll start the next because I want you to be sure and read it.

715
01:06:44,800 --> 01:06:46,080
Yeah, go ahead.

716
01:06:46,080 --> 01:06:48,481
Oh, and you put it a little too weakly.

717
01:06:48,481 --> 01:06:53,080
You can have meaning with an adult without knowing it at all.

718
01:06:53,080 --> 01:06:54,920
In fact, knowing it would undermine it.

719
01:06:54,920 --> 01:06:58,681
I mean, one, luckily, you can't, you were never going to be able to know it.

720
01:06:58,681 --> 01:06:59,960
It's unrepresentable.

721
01:06:59,960 --> 01:07:12,681
If you could know it, if you could have a science of proxemics, which I think I mentioned once, which had the whole theory of distance standing in our culture, I think you'd probably get so inhibited about distance standing you wouldn't be able to do it anymore.

722
01:07:14,361 --> 01:07:18,760
All these practices only work when you don't think about them.

723
01:07:18,760 --> 01:07:24,521
It's like trying to think about while you're riding a bicycle how you do it or dance or how you do it.

724
01:07:24,521 --> 01:07:34,200
So being in your culture, standing your way and looking people in the eye your way and so forth is something you can only do when you don't represent it.

725
01:07:34,201 --> 01:07:36,441
And that's good though to make that point.

726
01:07:36,681 --> 01:07:40,760
It's not just, however you put it, sort of better if you don't understand it.

727
01:07:41,080 --> 01:07:54,441
I think it's one understand, it's one, it's not representable and understandable, and two, it's a very important and positive thing that you can't understand it, according to Melville, and according to me, and Heidegger, at least and Nietzsche, I think.

728
01:07:54,840 --> 01:08:00,040
Okay, let me just set up the next thing because I want you to have it to read.

729
01:08:00,361 --> 01:08:06,440
The second kind of meaning, this is all sort of pure pagan meanings.

730
01:08:06,441 --> 01:08:17,240
And now, a meaning which we still have, by the way, but which we are sort of lost a sense of the sacred of it.

731
01:08:17,241 --> 01:08:21,400
And in a way, I think, could we be losing our practices?

732
01:08:21,401 --> 01:08:22,681
Hmm.

733
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:27,320
That's a long story, I think.

734
01:08:27,321 --> 01:08:40,240
But there's something to be said for the fact that in our culture, our practices actually operate so as to try to force us to make everything explicit and understanding.

735
01:08:40,561 --> 01:08:48,400
The latest version is try to get it all so you can represent it on a computer, so that you can make a computer that will behave like a human being.

736
01:08:48,401 --> 01:09:05,760
Well, if a lot of what makes people behave like a human being is the non-representable stuff in their way of dealing with everything, then you'd better be able to make to represent it into the computer so you can have artificial intelligence and make a computer that behaves like people.

737
01:09:06,080 --> 01:09:08,320
And people try that.

738
01:09:08,561 --> 01:09:10,240
That's proxemics, for instance.

739
01:09:10,241 --> 01:09:15,040
Let's make a computer that has all the theory in it of distance standing, whatever.

740
01:09:15,521 --> 01:09:26,880
And so our practices lead us to try to make them explicit and try to cover up their unrepresentableness.

741
01:09:26,880 --> 01:09:28,240
It's a funny situation.

742
01:09:28,241 --> 01:09:30,720
Heidegger worries about it a lot.

743
01:09:31,361 --> 01:09:34,160
That isn't what you should be thinking about or worrying about.

744
01:09:34,160 --> 01:09:34,800
It isn't.

